<br>
On the way there I thought about whether I would accept a donation for my trouble (10-20 minutes of time lost), but I decided I wouldn't. When I got there, I found that it was a dwarf paladin who needed the rez and then was sure I wouldn't.<br>
<br>
After rezzing him, he said &quot;thanks&quot; and sat down. I set to med back some mana before heading back out and a few minutes later he zoned into Chardok (his body had been right at the zone), without another word.<br>
<br>
Now, this is a case where I wouldn't have accepted a copper but I was a bit annoyed with the gratitude shown for my trouble - an offer of a donation or a bit of roleplaying would have been plenty. Here's the thing - a show of appreciation itself can be rewarding; most people at least one some acknowledgment that they went out of their way to assist you (the same &quot;thanks&quot; given for a sow at the bank isn't much).<br>
<br>
Not that the experience changes my view in any way, but it is interesting how some people take it for granted that others will help them. If anything, the person's friend was much more appreciative than the person being aided. All in all, I guess I should be glad I got to use my rez. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=231378">Romidar Trueblade</a>
